{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b41c38d-ab38-4b63-aa5a-79535769e3f1","content":"## What happened\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, overload resolution changed so that `array.Contains(item)` now prefers **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in LINQ expression trees — the expression tree interpreter blows up at runtime.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nForce the compiler back to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by disambiguating the receiver type:\n\n**Option A — cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nEither form ensures the compiler picks the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which is expression-tree safe.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c53e51a7-3376-4c3a-ac64-4f2dad18fa45","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays. Let me think about this.\n\nIn .NET 10 / C# 14, there's a known breaking change related to how the compiler resolves extension methods. Specifically, C# 14 introduces **extension members** (a new feature), and the compiler's overload resolution for extension methods changed.\n\nThe key issue: In earlier versions of C#, `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]` would resolve to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`. \n\nBut in C# 14 / .NET 10, the compiler now prefers `System.MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead, which can't be represented in expression trees since it uses `Span<T>` parameters. MemoryExtensions.Contains` over `Enumerable.Contains` for array types and spans. The `MemoryExtensions.Contains` operates on `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and since `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` types cannot be used in expression trees (they're ref structs), this would cause a compilation error or runtime error.\n\nBut the user says it throws at runtime, not compile time. If the expression tree was built dynamically or with an older compiler, it could fail at runtime instead. Looking at the `preferInterpretation: true` flag—that uses the expression tree interpreter rather than IL emission, which might handle this differently.\n\nThe real issue is likely that C# 14 now resolves `array.Contains(num)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, and since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` can't be represented in expression trees, the compiler should reject this at compile time—but maybe the expression tree is being constructed programmatically at runtime, and that's when the method resolution fails. I'm realizing the issue might stem from how the compiler resolves `Contains` differently across .NET versions—if it's picking `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, that can't be represented in an expression tree at compile time. But since the user reports a runtime error, maybe they're dynamically building the expression tree or there's a version mismatch between compilation and execution. cannot be represented in expression trees, so the compiler either rejects the conversion at compile time or the runtime interpreter fails when it tries to execute the tree. The user mentioned a runtime error, which suggests the expression tree was built successfully but fails during interpretation—possibly because .NET 9 or 10 changed how `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is resolved for arrays, and the expression tree can't handle the ref struct parameter.\n\nLet me trace through the .NET 8/9 breaking changes around `Contains` overloads and see if C# 14 introduced stricter rules about which methods can appear in expression trees.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that C# 14's new extension member resolution logic inadvertently changed how `array.Contains(item)` gets resolved—it now picks `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains`, and since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, it can't be used in expression trees. The workaround is to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` to force the right overload. I'm realizing the distinction matters here—if the compiler detects the incompatibility at compile time, it would throw an error immediately, but if the expression tree somehow gets built and only fails during interpretation at runtime, that's a different scenario. The most likely explanation is that in C# 14, the compiler might not catch this in expression tree contexts, allowing the tree to reference `MemoryExtensions.Contains`, which then fails when the runtime tries to interpret parameters like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`.\n\nThe core issue is that `Contains` now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)` for arrays, but ref structs can't be used in expression trees. Since the user is seeing a runtime error, I should focus on how to disambiguate the method call to force the `Enumerable` version instead.","outputTokens":2892,"requestId":"282E:61634:ACF0EA:C949CD:69EABD7B"},"id":"e26f0051-21e5-41f4-a04c-a9d7447ce0b8","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:48.114Z","parentId":"9d42170e-e56e-4254-9a93-942d68721d20"}
